The first thing you have to understand about Portland, Oregon is the definition of "weird". The unofficial town slogan, on the back of a building that serves as a pizza joint, bar, music venue, strip club, and skirts the law on at least half of these endeavors, is "Keep Portland Weird". To some, this is a small cry to remember the Portland of the 90's and early 2000's, a Portland that was less known and less expensive, generating creative and unique subcultures. To others, it is a beckoning call - come to Portland, where people will still call you weird, but as a compliment this time. Despite the influx of affluent Californians and the constant construction of condominiums to house these Californians, Portland is still weird. Weird does not mean always accepting, but it does mean accepting of things that are normally not accepted. Weird does not mean we do not have modern conveniences and modern fights. Like the rest of the country, we buy most of our things from China. There are a million ways of being weird, of being not normal, but Portland has plenty of normal. Portland has yoga and hipsters and business professionals. Perhaps weird means we just take all of this less seriously. In my neighborhood, as in many Portland neighborhoods, we have colorful houses, home gardens with flowers and herbs and vegetables lining the streets, and free boxes in the summertime. Free boxes are traditionally cardboard boxes containing items someone is getting rid of, but they can be plastic bags or boxes. They contain something magical, a treasure just perfect for the person wandering by, a surprising amount of the time. Free boxes tend to have clothes and books, but they can have anything. The magical potential of walking through a Southeast Portland neighborhood is what Portland is all about. That is, what Portland is all about to me, but I am just one variety of weird among thousands. Some people I live among would never dream of picking their clothes out of a box on the sidewalk. Those people go to goat yoga (yes, yoga with real live goats) or Timbers matches (the city's soccer team). Portland is full of people who love all sorts of things. Portland is full of people who pursue our dreams, or dream about pursuing our dreams while spending too much time at the bar. Yes, Portland has a drug problem. Drug problems tend to be (at their root) mental health problems, and the constant rain through much of the year, plus the dreary clouds, appear to be a contributor. Portland has a homelessness problem too, which no one seems to know what to do with. The homeless population is drawn by the social services Portland offers, better than in most parts of the country, but our services are insufficient, as in all parts of the country. The non-homeless population wavers between care and hatred. In this, we are not weird at all.
The mountains are always there. In the north, bearing witness to the sun’s journey every dawn and every dusk. No matter how much I forget about them or how caught up with work and life I am to notice, they are there, unwavering, unopposed, and unphased by life’s tribulations. Then on days when I am the most stressed and wound, they demand to be seen, and when I turn to them they let me rest my anxious soul, lending me some strength to go on, one day at a time. I first moved here when I started my undergrad, and the mountains to the north of campus where what first captivated me. Sure, the university has its own share of breathtaking sights in buildings and ponds and trees, which have their own share of my heart, but it’s the mountains that really holds its throne. The rest of the town is beautiful in its own right. There are countless cafés that were home to many hours of caffeine fueled cramming. One can walk or take the bus just a little further to the downtown area and be enveloped in an aura of antiquity by the faded colored bricks that line restaurants and office buildings. It is here that this seemingly suburban town shows as much bustle and vigor as it’s neighboring urban city. This doesn’t last for many blocks though, as one can escape, once again, to the serene small town by passing the library. This dichotomy of atmospheres in such proximity truly give this city a wonderous vibe as if it was beckoning to be explored. With this, it is easy to create many a cherished memory, each in association with a certain part of town. Whether it is walking past the rusted swings in the park with friends after an all-nighter or running through the busy downtown to catch the movie in the fancy theater for which the university provided tickets. Alas, it is also home to many harsh memories, as all places are bound to be in life. The ponds, in particular, can be a rather fitting place for reflection as well as crying sessions at two in the morning in the middle of an existential crisis. The latter of which, I have more experience in. While watching the turtles and ducks and insects live out their lives, each with some contribution or role, I couldn’t help but wonder about my own sense of purpose as I struggled to navigate this mystery called life. So, I walked past the pond, and past the park and little houses that scream of suburbia, until I reached a main street. It was then that sun shined its brilliant rays atop the palm trees, painting the sky along the way, and as I looked up at the sunrise, I realized I was walking north. Sure enough, they were there, as they had always been. The sturdy overbearing mountains grazed the hazy blue and yellow sky more than any building in the horizon, and as if speaking without words, stirred in me my sense of perseverance.
You might pass it up on first glance - after all, it is a residential area behind a shopping strip, not a place one would assume there are places to live. At least, not places most people would want to live. But if you go behind the old, abandoned Whole Foods and walk back behind the hotels which are only occupied annually aside from a few stints in the summertime for family reunions, you'll find an entire bustling community. Within these communities, on these streets, are a handful of apartment complex - situated next to each other carefully like Russian nesting dolls that have been scrupulously, carefully taken apart and set beside each other in a line down the road, piecemeal. The first apartments you come upon are ones which have been on the news for some fairly unsavory dealings, so we won't focus on those too much - appearances, after all, can be deceiving. But the apartments beside that complex, and the two complexes beside that one, are a whole other world that almost no one living in this area knows about. Across from those complexes is a community college's satellite campus - a quiet, sleepy set of buildings standing sentinel beside the road, where students putter in with coffee in hand, yawning at 7 in the morning to begin their sleepy days. The iron gates creak open to admit them one by one, while commuters shake their fists out the window and groan at them for holding up traffic on days attendance is higher. The road t-bones into another residential road, with a park on one side and a rehabilitation center for people who have broken bones in unfortunate circumstances. The treatment center boasts cheerful porch furniture, and a lazily undulating ceiling fan which churns the warm, thick summertime air back and forth. Children run back and forth in the grass at the park across the street, cartwheeling and pinwheeling across the prickly green stalks while bees lazily turn in the flower patches by the road. Old retired folks walk their dogs on the walking path, scowling at the teenagers on their skateboards and nodding demurely at the teenage girls clustered by the playground equipment, gossiping about boys and the latest YouTube sensations. There is a sushi place in a strip mall beside the park that has inexpensive food but never seems too busy - a swimming supply store right beside that, and a nail salon nestled in between. You could fill your pool for the season while getting a manicure and eating hibachi chicken, all at once - the beauty of a strip mall. There is a frozen yogurt place there too, one of the DIY kind, and you often see the teens in the park clutching cold, sweating cups of frozen yogurt covered in toppings while they do stunts on their skateboards and vape because they believe it to be the coolest. The neighborhood in question is a slice of Americana - a piece of history in the sleepy south where hardly anything changes, not even time.
My neighborhood is interesting. Most of the houses are single family, but there are a few homes that have been split into two, while still being attached, if that makes much sense. My home has a small yard in front of it and a small driveway to the left of the house. It, like most of the others, reminds you of a time not so long ago where living in the suburbs was the American dream. This dream at once seemed to embrace the people of this country, but now its pulling away. But my neighborhood and many more still remain, still call out to us and those who visit that the dream is still alive, and we are still holding onto it as best we can. The people don't feel as optomistic as they used to, the upkeep of the little yards are not what they used to be, but there is still a car or two in every driveway, still the youth play as if the world around them was the whole of their existence. The public school that has been here for almost 90 years still stands, still seems conjure a future in today's youth, while stirring up nostalgia in the older residents. The churches are few and far between, mostly empty, but the basketball courts are still full. All of the homes look different, but feel the same. There is a large supermarket called super "A" that has been owned by a large Yemni family, who are quite possible the only Arab family in the neighborhood. The vast majority of the residents are African American. The streets are wide and the kids usually play footbal, only stopping to allow the cars to pass. Most of the people in my neighborhood have been here for generations and most can tell stories of a past where everyone knew everyone. There was a karate school, but when hollywood stopped making karate kid movies, the kids stopped wanting to be the karate kid, so its now a pharmacy, because drugs make everything better, or so I've heard. There is also a small movie theatre that plays old movies at a discounted price, spared from the crowds by the youth's disdane for its lack of just release titles, but favored by the elders, who think it is a small price to pay for a night out, without the kids of course. There is a single expressway that passes through my town. Though the exit and entrance are in the town next to ours. There was once a petition to get and exit for our town. The youth supported it, while the elders refused. It seems that having the expressway in our town would ruin it, so said the elders who eventually persuaded the city council to deny the request. They are building a new highschool, and we are trying to decide on a mascott for our town. I think a cyborg with a country accent and a log cabin would be then best representation of my town.
Since I live in a large city, my neighborhood is extremely diverse. Residential areas are dispersed, seemingly randomly, between commercial areas, where a variety of businesses are run. Some of these businesses are made up of offices, while others are various stores, restaurants, and places of entertainment. There is no shortage of new restaurants to eat at, or stores to shop in. While some stores are large, well-known, brands that are owned by large corporations, small boutiques are also increasingly popular. They are not only located in various malls, but they also line the streets, which are often in walking distance of neighborhoods that would otherwise be quiet and serene, if not surrounded by so many points of interest. There are also a couple of nearby parks, and I have noticed that people frequent these parks with their young children. Speaking of the people, thereâ€™s actually quite a bit of diversity within my neighborhood. In one small location, we have a prominent LGBTQ+ community, an Orthodox Jewish community, and a collection of refugees and immigrants from the former Soviet Union. Spanning a little further outside of my neighborhood, there are many more individuals of various races and origins, although they are sometimes broken up into their own little communities within the city. We have locations known as Korea town, China town, Little Armenia, and many more, which are only a few miles away. However, only a few miles can prove to be a very lengthy drive. Driving a distance of only 10 miles can sometimes span two hours, due to traffic, especially during rush hour. Hardly anyone in my city walks anywhere, though. While certain locations of interest are inevitably close-by, the city is huge, and people do not generally prefer to commute on foot. As a result, we also have some of the worst traffic in the world, and it can be difficult to find parking spots just about anywhere. Ironically enough, there has been a great deal of construction in recent years, as large apartment buildings are being added to the city. It is seems to be a popular destination, but many residents are disappointed by the prospect of even more people moving in, and even more vehicles on the roads. There are many different types of houses in my city, however. Not everyone lives, or wishes to live, in a large apartment building. Residential areas are made up of houses, of various sizes, and smaller apartment buildings and condominiums. Some properties contain single-family homes, while others contain duplexes. This is true even within my immediately neighborhood, so there is also no lack of diversity in regards to housing options. Similarly, the neighborhood is made up of people of varying ages, and to be perfectly honest, I am not familiar with the majority of my neighbors. It is not really a tight-knit community these days, although I have many memories from my childhood of playing outside with my next-door neighbor, and a few other friends from the neighborhood, who were all close to my age.
“Where is everything?” she asked as we drove past the corn fields which filled the horizon. “This is it!” I said, knowing she’d be in shock of the sparseness of the open landscape. She was from a town in which the grocery store was a 5 minute walk from her house--she’d never seen this much open space in her life. Taken back by the ubiquity of corn fields, I shared with her what it was like to grow up in rural Ohio, and in that moment, she finally knew who I was and where I came from. Driving down a two-lane country road, you will reach a quarry which is filled with water. Just past it is the small development I live in. The houses are mostly composed of brick and stucco. All the houses have at least a half an acre of land to themselves which everyone takes pride in maintaining. During springtime, annually planted flowers are abundant along with the midwestern trees that change with every season. The driveways are all filled with the highest end Mercedes Benz luxury cars that glisten in the midday sun after a good, old-fashioned car wash. Continuing along the road toward my grey stucco home, my Korean neighbor is always outside with a friendly face. He tends to spend the entire day mowing his lawn and can be heard singing over his mower’s hum. Everyone in the neighborhood gets a laugh out of him, but he is always genuine and an amazing person with a unique history. He has grown older and has lost some of his wit as he aged. In his past he was a doctor and usually blends in with the grass and his John Deer Zero Turn mower. Finally, you will reach my home. In the side yard, geese are abundant and are chased by our Terrier. Out back, there is a small stream that feeds into the quarry. Here, you can hear bullfrogs, the stream, and the occasional “moo” from the nearby farms. Across the handmade wooden bridge is an untouched oasis filled with naturally growing trees, herbs, and wildflowers. Here was where I spent most of my childhood. From building tree forts to ‘hunting’ animals (which mostly consisted of chasing them), there was always something to do and usually a neighborhood child available for friendship. The winters in my small town can be painfully brutal, yet there is nothing more beautiful. The yard transforms from a sea of green into an empty wilderness. The trees that once housed vibrant pink, purple, and orange flowers turn into barren skeletons of bark. When blessed with the occasional snowfall, a winter wonderland appears overnight. The backyard is lined with snow angels made by my little sister, and snowmen. My sister and I fought frequently as kids, and during the winter, snowballs were our weapon of choice. We’d build massive igloo-like forts to house our weapons, usually with branches, like an arsenal. In our own little wonderland was where we played pretend during a time where nothing else mattered. We were just young kids without a care in the world.
transformed_texts:
I live in a small town in Michigan, far from big cities. Here, farms meet small towns that welcome visitors. We do not have large stores or many restaurants. You must drive to get anywhere you need to go.

Still, I live in one of the most beautiful places in America. My town sits between two large lakes - Lake Michigan and Lake Charlevoix. You can find many beaches to enjoy the water.

In my part of town, the houses stand far apart. Each house looks different and many are old. Most have rooms under the ground that you can see from the street. The houses come in many colors, and most have big yards. Children play on swings and jump on trampolines in these yards. Some people grow plants for food or keep animals behind fences.

The people who live here work hard and raise families. Every day, you see children playing in the streets. People walk their dogs or ride bikes. Neighbors know each other well. They wave and smile when they meet. Everyone keeps their grass cut and their yards clean.

This is not the most beautiful place, but it is good for families. It is quiet and safe. Near my house, you can walk to important places like the police building and the health office. There are fields where people play ball games. Small planes fly from our town's airport. Children can ride bikes to get ice cream or go to the park.

This is a very good place to live.

I live in a planned neighborhood in the outer part of a city. There is a group that makes rules for all the houses here. When you come into our area, you see many houses that look alike. Each house has a small green yard in front with rocks and small trees. Every house has space for two cars. The roads are very smooth and clean.

Most houses have one floor, but some have two floors. We do not have mailboxes in front of our houses. Instead, we all get our mail from a group of boxes at the end of the street. We use keys to get our mail, and there are special boxes for bigger things that come in the mail.

My neighborhood is between city and country areas. We have a lot of space here. There are several swimming pools that everyone who lives here can use. The pools have gates around them. We also have paths where people can walk their dogs or take walks. You can exercise here without going to a special place.

Many older people who have stopped working live here. It is very safe, and people watch out for each other. Some younger working people live here too. Our city is big when you count the people, but it feels small. We have one shopping center. It is not very big, but it works well for us. 

It takes about fifteen minutes by car to get to stores. We have many different kinds of stores. Some sell healthy food at high prices, and others sell fewer things for less money. 

My neighborhood is a good place to live. It is safe and clean. We have nice things like pools and walking paths. While stores are not very close, we can drive to any store we need.

I first learned about my home while listening to a radio show about missing people. This surprised me. Most homes in this area cost more than one thousand dollars each month to live in. None of my friends knew about these stories either. Life can be hard here. Some of my friends cry at night because things cost so much money. We have learned to live with less.

The smell of used things becomes normal. Old toys and clothes from second-hand stores have a special smell. As you get older, you notice smells less. Some people start smoking. Others just get used to how things are. The smell of old books on an unused piano becomes normal. Even after washing, the smell stays in things made of leather.

There are three second-hand stores near my home. I can walk to them all. There are also two places that sell used things to help people in need, a library, a store with rare books, and a shop with interesting old things. Many cars and people fill the streets every morning in the center of town. But inside these stores, it is very quiet. It is nice to spend time there.

More people come to our city every year. They say our city is growing. A big company that sells things on the internet has its main office here. This reminds me of New York City. Everyone follows their own path, and no one asks too many questions. You can be by yourself, and people will let you be. It is not like the southern part of our country, where asking about others shows you care.

I live near people who play piano and sing. We have become friends instead of just people who live near each other. We help each other, share happy times, and support each other when sad things happen. I am lucky to be here. My neighbors are kind, and I try to be kind too. We share food and help with mail. Even though I live in a big city that can feel cold, my neighbors make it feel like home.

I live in a small town near a big city in the middle of America. My part of town, on the east side, is where many people with less money live. Houses here do not cost much, and most people rent them. Still, it is a nice place. People who live near me are friendly and say hello when I walk by.

While crime is a bit higher here than in other parts of town, it is still mostly safe. There have been some bad events near my home in the past ten years, including some shootings. Our neighbors lost their son last year when he was shot near a local bar. My family has been lucky, though we sometimes lose small things from our front steps if we forget to bring them inside.

Like many places in America, our town has problems with dangerous drugs. Many people have died from taking bad medicine. However, there are places here that help people who want to stop using drugs. They also teach families how to help loved ones who might take too much.

Even with these problems, there are many good things about my town. My son goes to a very good school. The teachers and other workers there are wonderful. Even though my son has special needs, other children are kind to him, and he is very happy there. Parents and teachers work together to make the school better. Because many families here do not have much money, all children get free food at school. No one is treated badly because they cannot pay, and school activities do not cost much.

The town leaders have made many things look better. They fixed roads and made parks nicer. But most of these changes happened in the middle of town and on the west side, where the stores are. The east side, where I live, often gets left out. This makes people in my area unhappy.

Still, I like living here. People are nice, the schools are good, and we have enough stores to buy what we need. Our house may not be worth much money, but it is comfortable. We have lived here for more than 16 years, and we want to stay here.

I live in a special part of town called Hilltop. It sits on high ground, with many old buildings around it. My home is in a tall building across from a theater. Down the street, there is a place where people play games and drink. Many people come there when the weather is warm.

Near my home is a city park. It is big, with concrete walls and steps around it. In winter, people who have no homes put their tents on the steps and near the sidewalk. It does not snow much here, but it rains a lot. These people stay close to each other to keep warm. They can also walk to a place where they can wash.

What makes this area special is not just the old buildings or how it looks. It is the people who live here. Years ago, Hilltop was known as a dangerous place. The government tried to make it safer. People still tell stories about those times.

Today, people work hard to keep the area clean and safe. Some say white people should not walk here at night. I think this idea comes from old fears. Maybe because my skin is not fully white, or maybe because I am now part of this community, I feel safe here.

This place shows that our country still has problems with how people think about each other. But Hilltop is my home. People here are kind. Once, when I needed help, the person at the laundry place let me stay late to charge my phone. Another time, when I was sitting alone in the rain, someone gave me money and told me I matter.

No matter where I go, Hilltop will always be my home.

I came to live in this area when I was ready to start my last year of middle school. At first, it was not easy to find friends, but I became close with two boys who lived on my street. They have moved away now, but I still remember our time together. Most people who lived here when I first came still live here today.

My area looks like many other places where Americans live outside big cities. There are many houses with two floors. When the weather is warm, I can hear children playing outside. Most days are quiet here. I have never had trouble with anyone who lives nearby. People here leave you alone unless you need help. When I get things sent to my house, no one takes them. I feel safe with my neighbors.

There is a small park very close to my house. I have many good memories there. I played many games there with other boys, like basketball and football. Once, I got hurt playing football there, but most memories are good. Now, I go there with my young cousins. They love to play on the swings and slides. They get very happy when we talk about going to the park. When I go there now, it makes me think about old times.

Many different kinds of people live here. You can find food from many places nearby. Within a short walk, you can get Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian food. Many people now use their phones to have food brought to them. There are also many places that sell quick food and pizza.

You can find all the stores you need here. There are places to clean clothes, drug stores, and a big food store. There is even a store that sells Indian food and things to make Indian meals at home.

I really like living in this area. When I read about problems other people have where they live, I am very happy with my neighborhood.

I live near my college, which makes me happy. The area has many apartment buildings and some places to eat and drink that do not cost too much. There is one bar with a new name that costs more, but it is still okay to visit. Most people who live here are nice. Many are students or people who do not have much money, as the apartments are not expensive. There are many children around because there is a school close by.

I do not know the people who live next to me, and that is fine. They smoke a lot, so the building owners put something in the hall to make the air smell better. My friend and I think this is funny. Most buildings here are old on the outside but some look better inside. There are new apartments down the street, but they were not built well. They cost a lot because they are near school.

There is a very cheap eating place near me where they serve food on paper plates. Next to it is a gas station. The city fixed the street last summer, adding new walking paths and grass, which made things look better. Many trees grow around my building, though some were cut down. Behind my building are more trees and more apartments.

I live on 42nd Street. The street behind mine, 43rd Street, does not look as nice. The walking paths there are broken, and the buildings do not look good. The trees there help hide how the buildings look. Bad things sometimes happen in that area, and also across from where I live.

Still, I like living here. I can pay for it, and everything I need is close. I like that I can walk to school, and I can take a bus to the store or to the center of town.

I live in a special group of houses. Each house is actually two homes put together, but they look like single homes. They all have yellow walls, white front areas, and green metal tops. Most people who live here are friends. In the evening, we often meet and talk while children play with their toys or draw with chalk on the ground. Sometimes they fly kites, too.

Living here feels like going back to an earlier time, away from today's world of computers. We have fields and trees all around us, with blue sky and white clouds above. The only bad thing is that we sometimes get warnings about strong storms. Last night, we heard loud warning sounds telling us to find safe places to hide.

I went to my bathroom with my small dog, some soft things to sit on, and my bag. My big dog stayed in the living room, making loud sounds because he was afraid. Outside, ice fell from the sky, and then the road made steam because the weather got much cooler very fast. When the storm ended, the sun came out while it was still raining, and two beautiful colored lines appeared in the sky. I took pictures to show my friends.

After an hour, people came back outside. Mothers watched their children play while food was cooking. I moved here from the north, and I like how people talk here in the south. My home has two rooms for sleeping and two rooms for washing. All homes look the same outside, but they are different inside.

I enjoy walking in the big field behind my house. There is a small lake there, but we cannot swim in it. I see deer sometimes, and in the morning, I hear big frogs making sounds. I live forty minutes away from the big city. Every morning, I hear farm birds making their morning sounds. There is even a special animal like a horse that makes loud sounds in the evening. I am very happy I found this nice place to live.

I have lived in this area for ten years and would like to share my story. When we first moved from Riverdale to Stockbridge, I felt very sad. I cried because I missed my old friends. However, my parents wanted better things for me and my little sister. They chose this area because it had better houses and a good high school.

Over time, I made new friends at school. I did not know many people who lived near us, except for Mr. Glen and Dennis, who live next door. They became like family to us. I remember going to Mr. Glen's wedding with my family. It was a very happy day. At the wedding, I caught the small white band that Ms. Veda threw from her leg. We danced and had fun with their daughter Marsharii, though I have not seen her since then.

Our area is like a maze, but now I use a map system to find my way. I often spent time with my friends Kason and Curtis playing games. I also like going to the park. Being in nature makes me feel calm and peaceful. I practice keeping my balance with sticks I bought from the store. Sometimes I bring my wooden practice sword.

The park has places to play basketball and tennis. While I have not played these sports lately, it is good to know they are there. My father taught me and my best friend how to play tennis with Mr. Graves. They made us work hard, but we had fun.

I have many good memories here. I believe even better times are coming in the future.

I live in Johnston, a small town in South Carolina. While it may look like many other towns, it is special because of its peaches. In fact, our town calls itself the Peach Capital of the World, and we show this proudly on our welcome sign.

Most of our land is used for growing peaches or raising cows. Houses outside the town center sit far apart from each other. Many have two floors with metal or gray tops to help stay cool in the hot summer. These homes often sit far from the road, with fields in front for animals or growing food.

In the middle of town, we have one traffic light where four roads meet. This is where you find our few stores. We have three places to eat: a Chinese family restaurant called Hong Kong, a Mexican place called Fiesta, and a burger shop called Gary's.

We have a small drug store called Maxwell and Halford, known for its special cola drinks. Our only food store is IGA, but it is expensive. Many people drive to the bigger town of Batesburg-Leesville to shop at Walmart. The busiest store in town is Dollar General, which sells many everyday things.

There is a furniture store called Possibilities, run by a friendly woman everyone knows. Next door is Clark's, where people can take their pets for cleaning and care. We have one doctor's office and one animal doctor's office, both small but good at helping our town's people.

Johnston has one school for young children. Older students must go to school in another town. We do not have a park yet, but the town is building one that will be quite big. We hope this will give families more things to do and bring new people to our town.

While we do not have movies, games, or many restaurants, Johnston is still a nice place. It is so small that you might miss it if you drive through too fast!

I live in a small town in Tennessee. My home is on a street that connects two big roads. Many cars pass by our house each day. Still, it is mostly quiet here. People stay in their homes for many years, so we know most of our neighbors well.

People here spend time working in their yards. In winter, children ride sleds down a nearby hill. Our house sits at the front of the street, so we see everyone who comes and goes. We know which cars belong here, and we notice when we see new ones.

Some people walk for exercise or with their dogs. Children ride bikes in the street. My family stays home a lot because we work from our house. There are four of us - my wife, our two daughters who are eleven and fourteen, and me. We play outside often, even when it rains.

Sometimes we cook food outside on our back deck. The smell of cooking food is very nice. From spring to fall, someone is always cutting grass. You can hear lawn mowers almost every day until the cold comes.

We have many trees in our area. This gives us nice shade, but it also means many leaves fall in autumn. We must clean up these leaves and burn them each year. I like how burning leaves smell. It tells us autumn is here. Recently, winters have been warm, so it feels like autumn lasts longer.

Our car space is behind our house, so we rarely use the front door. When I work on my truck in the car space, I can see and hear what happens in our area. During special days like Thanksgiving and Christmas, it is quiet except for visiting cars. Many families have guests, so more cars park on our street.

I am happy living here. If fewer cars used our street as a way to other places, it would be perfect.

I live in the high desert where there is mostly brown dirt everywhere you look. Green grass is rare here because water costs too much. When I moved here in the 1990s, houses were far apart. Today, there are more houses, but they are still spread out. Our area is growing into a bigger town, like many other places.

Most people here are friendly. Like all towns, some areas are better than others. I live among nice older people in a good area. We have regular stores that you find in many places, but no expensive shops. To find special stores, we must drive far.

Many people here work building houses and buildings. This is because our town still has much empty land to build on. This worries me because I like our town as it is now. I moved away from a big city and want to stay in a smaller place. I work in building too, putting up walls and ceilings.

What I really like here are the animals. The desert is beautiful in its own way. Many special animals and plants live here, and we must protect them. People who live here should learn about these desert animals to live safely with them. My three children love the desert animals, especially the lizards and insects. They often try to catch them to look at them.

Our town, Victorville, has some interesting places to visit. The San Bernardino County Fair comes every year and is fun for families. Near us is Wrightwood, where people can see snow and learn winter sports. The Victor Valley Museum shows interesting things from our area's past, including rocks, old bones, Native American items, and things that tell how our town grew.

My neighborhood is different from what most people might describe. I live on a college campus, and my main community is the people in my dormitory building. The larger campus area is also part of what I think of as my neighborhood.

Even though this is not a usual neighborhood, it has many of the same things you would find in other places. There are places to live, people, shops, and a park.

There are three different kinds of places where people live here. First, there are apartment buildings. In these, two to four people share one room, and there are four to six rooms on each floor. Most apartment buildings have two floors, so about twenty people live in each one. Second, there are regular houses that people who work at or graduated from the school can rent. These houses usually have two to four bedrooms, but there are not many of them. Third, there are the dormitory buildings, which are the most common. In these buildings, hundreds of students live, usually with two people sharing one room.

The people who live here come from many different places and cultures. The school workers usually live in the houses. New students live in the dormitory buildings, while older students often live in the apartments.

Our neighborhood has many stores and a park. You can find places to eat, buy clothes, and get food from grocery stores. Everything we need is right here in our neighborhood. The park is a place where everyone can spend time outside. All of us who live here help keep it clean and safe.

I live in a place with few walking paths. My house is at the top of a very steep hill. Many people who exercise like to run up this hill. Since there are no walking paths, people must walk on the road. The road has holes and can be dangerous to drive on.

The power lines above look old and broken. It rains a lot here, and falling tree parts often break the power lines. Workers must fix them often, making them look strange.

There are many tall green trees here. But people do not like these trees because they block the view of the water. That is why houses are built high on the hill. They have big windows on their second floors to see the water below. When the sun goes down, the water looks bright and the sky turns orange. Most days are gray and wet, though. Green plant growth covers everything: house tops, cars, and metal bars. Once, I left my car outside for a month. When I came back, it was green all over. It took three hours to clean.

Not many young people live here, even though there is a school nearby. Most people who live here are older and do not work anymore. Instead of children, people have dogs. You often see dogs in yards or running in the street. Sometimes they even come into houses if doors are left open. I found one in my living room once and had to make it leave.

There are many wild rabbits here. They are big, and people who grow plants do not like them because they dig holes in the ground. My cats hunt these rabbits. We also have many birds: small ones, tiny fast ones that drink flower water, and big hunting birds that sometimes fly by until black birds chase them away.

There are no stores near my house, but if you walk down to the water, you can find places to eat fresh fish. There is not much sand by the water, but you can throw rocks into it. The water is not very wide. You can see the other side even when the air is not clear.

Bensonhurst is a part of Brooklyn that is easy to find. You can get there using public transportation, which many people in New York City use. The area feels like a city neighborhood.

Today, many Asian people live in Bensonhurst. In the past twenty years, more Asian families have moved here. You will see many Asian-owned stores on every street. There are many food stores and places to wash clothes. Local people like these stores because the food is good, prices are low, and the stores are close to their homes. Near my house, there are four Asian food stores that I can walk to in two minutes.

The area has people from many different places. Many families came from other countries, and their children were born here. While many businesses are owned by Asian people, the neighborhood has other people too.

There is a nice park nearby that was fixed up recently. It has many basketball courts, a big field for sports, places to play handball, and a playground for children. In summer, children can play in the water. People from different backgrounds play together here.

Most people live in two-family houses. There are some tall buildings where people can buy or rent homes. The people are friendly, but it can be loud. Cars often play loud music, and some drivers make noise with their cars early in the morning.

At night, you should be careful. While the area is mostly safe, some people might cause problems. There are bullies and people who steal. Someone once hurt me here years ago. Today, people sometimes steal packages left outside homes.

One problem is that some people do not clean up after their dogs. Even though there is a fine in New York City for this, you will see dog waste on the streets when you walk to the train or store. This makes walking around unpleasant, so watch where you step!

Portland, Oregon is a special city with its own way of being different. On a building that serves food, drinks, and music, you can see the words "Keep Portland Different." Some people want to remember how the city was twenty years ago when fewer people lived here and life cost less money. Others see it as a welcome sign to come and be different.

Many people from California have moved here, and new buildings keep going up. Still, Portland stays different. The city accepts things that other places might not. We have normal things too, like stores and businesses. People do yoga, work in offices, and shop like everyone else. Maybe we just worry less about being normal.

In my area, houses are painted in bright colors. People grow flowers and food in their front yards. In summer, we put boxes on the street with free things inside. These boxes often have clothes and books, but sometimes you find special things you did not expect. Walking through these streets makes Portland special to me.

Other people enjoy Portland in their own ways. Some go to special exercise classes with small farm animals. Others watch our city's soccer team play. Portland has many people who try to make their dreams come true. Some work hard at this, while others talk about it while drinking with friends.

Portland has problems too. Some people use drugs, perhaps because our weather is often dark and rainy. We also have many people without homes. The city tries to help them more than other places do, but it is not enough. Some people want to help those without homes, while others do not. In this way, Portland is like any other city.

The mountains stand in the north. They watch the sun rise and set each day. Even when I am too busy with work to notice them, they remain strong and steady. On hard days when my mind is troubled, the mountains catch my eye. Looking at them helps calm my worried thoughts and gives me strength to continue.

I came here as a student. The mountains near the school were the first thing that caught my attention. The school itself is beautiful, with nice buildings and small lakes with trees. But the mountains are what I love most.

The town is lovely too. There are many coffee shops where I spent long hours studying. A short bus ride takes you to the old part of town, where old brick buildings hold restaurants and offices. This area feels as busy as a big city. But walk past the library, and you find quiet streets again. Having both busy and quiet areas so close makes this town special, like it wants people to explore it.

I have many good memories here. I remember walking with friends by the old park swings after staying up all night. I remember running to catch movies at the nice theater downtown. But there are sad memories too. I often sat by the small lakes late at night, thinking about life while watching turtles and ducks in the water. I would wonder about my place in the world when things seemed hard to understand.

Sometimes I would walk past the lakes, through the quiet streets with small houses, until I reached a main road. One morning, as the sun came up and lit the palm trees, I looked north. There they were, as always - the strong mountains touching the morning sky. Without words, they reminded me to keep going.

At first, you might not notice this special place. It sits behind some stores, where most people would not expect to find homes. But if you walk past the empty food store and the hotels that are mostly quiet except in summer, you will find many people living there.

On these streets, there are several apartment buildings. They stand next to each other like toys in a row. The first building you see has had some problems, so we will not talk about it much. The other buildings next to it are different and special. Most people who live in this area do not know about them.

Across the street, there is a small college. Every morning at seven, tired students come with their coffee. They enter through big metal gates while people in cars wait, sometimes not very happily.

The street meets another road where there is a park on one side and a medical center on the other. The medical center has chairs on its front porch and a fan that moves slowly in the warm air. At the park, children play in the grass while bees fly around the flowers. Older people walk their dogs on the paths. They do not like the young people on skateboards but they smile at the girls who talk about boys near the play area.

Next to the park, there are some small stores. You can find a place that serves fish and rice, a store that sells things for swimming pools, and a place where people get their nails done. There is also a store where you can make your own frozen ice cream. Young people often get ice cream there and then go back to the park with their skateboards.

This neighborhood is like many other American places. It is in the quiet south where things stay the same for a long time.

I want to tell you about where I live. The houses in my area are mostly for one family, though some are split for two families to live in. My house has a small green space in front and a place for cars on the left side. These houses make me think about how people once wanted to live away from the city. Many people still live this way, but it is not as popular as before.

The people who live here try to keep their houses nice, but it is not easy. Every house has cars parked outside. Children play in the streets as if nothing else matters. The school has been here for many years. It gives young people hope and makes older people remember good times. The churches do not have many people now, but many young people still play basketball.

All houses look different but feel like home. There is a big food store run by a family from Yemen. Most people who live here are African American. The streets are wide, and children play games, moving only when cars need to pass. Many families have lived here for many years. They tell stories about times when everyone knew their neighbors.

We once had a place that taught fighting sports, but now it is a drug store. We have a small movie house that shows old films for less money. Young people do not go there much, but older people like it.

A big road passes near our town, but you cannot get on it here. Young people wanted a way to get on the big road from our town, but older people said no. They thought it would hurt our town. We are building a new school now. We need to pick something to represent our town. I think it should be something that shows both old and new ways of life.

I live in a big city where many different kinds of people live close to each other. My area has homes mixed with places where people work and shop. There are many offices, stores, restaurants, and places where people go to have fun.

There are always new places to eat and shop. Some stores are part of big companies that everyone knows. There are also many small stores owned by local people. These stores are in shopping centers and along the streets near quiet living areas.

There are parks nearby where families bring their children to play. Many different groups of people live here. We have gay and lesbian people, Jewish people who follow old ways, and people who came from Russia and nearby countries. If you go a little further, you can find areas where Chinese, Korean, and Armenian people live together.

Getting around the city is hard. A ten-mile trip can take two hours when there are many cars on the road. Most people drive cars instead of walking, even to close places. This makes it hard to find places to park, and the roads are always full.

They are building many new tall houses for people to live in. Some people who already live here are not happy about more people moving in because it means more cars on the roads. We have many kinds of homes here - big houses, small houses, and middle-sized houses where more than one family lives.

People of all ages live in my area, but I do not know many of my neighbors well. When I was young, I used to play outside with the children who lived next door, but now people do not spend as much time with their neighbors.

"What do you see here?" she asked as we drove past the corn fields that went as far as we could see. "This is all there is!" I said. I knew she would be surprised by how empty it looked. She came from a place where stores were close to her home. She had never seen so much open land before.

As we drove, I told her about growing up in Ohio's farming area. This helped her understand who I am. If you follow the small road, you will find a water-filled hole in the ground. My house is just past it, in a group of homes. The houses are made of brick and have large yards that people keep very nice. In spring, there are many flowers and trees that change with each season.

Nice cars sit in the driveways, clean and bright in the sun. Near my grey house lives a man from Korea. He spends much time cutting his grass and singing. People smile when they see him. He used to be a doctor and is now older. He rides his grass-cutting machine all day.

At my house, birds walk in the yard while our small dog runs after them. Behind the house, there is a small stream of water. You can hear frogs and sometimes cows from nearby farms. Past a wooden bridge I made, there is a beautiful area with trees, plants, and wild flowers. I spent much of my young life there. I built places in trees and played with friends who lived nearby.

The cold time of year can be hard, but it is very beautiful. The green yard becomes white. Trees that had bright flowers become empty. When snow falls, it makes everything look special. My younger sister made snow shapes on the ground and snow people. As children, we often played in the snow, throwing snow balls at each other. We built snow houses with branches to hide behind. In our own special place, we played without worry. We were just children having fun.
